14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Surgical treatment of
paraphimosis is carried out with the ineffectiveness of conservative
therapy;&nbsp;dissection of the restraining ring of the foreskin is performed,
followed by reduction of the glans penis.&nbsp;After the edema subsides, after
a few weeks, it is recommended to carry out a complete excision of the foreskin
(circumcision), which prevents the recurrence of paraphimosis.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Recovery
and improvement of the quality of life</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Rehabilitation after surgical
treatment of paraphimosis requires strict adherence to the doctor's
recommendations.&nbsp;For the first few days, the urologist monitors the
condition of the postoperative wound, teaches the patient how to wash properly,
and how to dress it.&nbsp;After discharge, thermal and water procedures are not
recommended (trips to baths, saunas).&nbsp;For 1 month, the patient should
limit physical activity, exclude sex life, masturbation.&nbsp;You need to rest
more, eat well.&nbsp;Full recovery can take up to 2-3 months.&nbsp;It all depends
on the degree of damage to the tissues of the penis and the volume of the
operation performed.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:18.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Possible complications</span></b></p>

